    "content": "<html>\n<head>\n    <title>Backpropagation</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>Backpropagation</h1>\n    <p>Backpropagation is an algorithm used in machine learning to train neural networks.</p>\n    <p>It works by adjusting the weights and biases of the network to minimize the error between the predicted output and the actual output.</p>\n    <p>Here is a simple implementation of backpropagation in JavaScript:</p>\n    <script>\n        // Define the sigmoid function\n        function sigmoid(x) {\n            return 1 / (1 + Math.exp(-x));\n        }\n\n        // Define the derivative of the sigmoid function\n        function sigmoidDerivative(x) {\n            return x * (1 - x);\n        }\n\n        // Define the mean squared error function\n        function mse(x, y) {\n            return (x - y) ** 2;\n        }\n\n        // Define the backpropagation function\n        function backpropagation(w, b, x, y, hidden, numLayers, epochs) {\n            // Initialize the error and weights\n            let error = mse(x, y);\n            let weights = Array(numLayers).fill(0).map(() => Array(hidden).fill(0));\n            let biases = Array(numLayers).fill(0).map(() => Array(hidden).fill(0));\n\n            // Train the network\n            for (let epoch = 0; epoch < epochs; epoch++) {\n                for (let i = 0; i < x.length; i++) {\n                    // Forward pass\n                    let hiddenOutput = sigmoid(dotProduct(w[0], x[i]));\n                    let output = sigmoid(dotProduct(w[1], hiddenOutput));\n                    let prediction = sigmoid(dotProduct(w[2], output));\n\n                    // Backward pass\n                    let errorGrad = mse(y[i], prediction) * hiddenOutput * (1 - hiddenOutput) * sigmoidDerivative(hiddenOutput);\n                    weights[0][0] -= 0.01 * errorGrad * x[i];\n                    weights[1][0] -= 0.01 * errorGrad * hiddenOutput;\n                    weights[2][0] -= 0.01 * errorGrad * prediction;\n                    biases[0][0] -= 0.01 * errorGrad;\n                    biases[1][0] -= 0.01 * errorGrad;\n                    biases[2][0] -= 0.01 * errorGrad;\n                }\n            }\n        }\n\n        // Define the dot product function\n        function dotProduct(w, x) {\n            return x.reduce((sum, val, i) => sum + val * w[i], 0);\n        }\n\n        // Define the input/output function\n        function inputOutput(w, b, x, y) {\n            return dotProduct(w, x) + b[0];\n        }\n\n        // Define the main function\n        function main() {\n            // Define the weights and biases\n            let w = Array(3).fill(0).map(() => Array(2).fill(0));\n            let b = Array(2).fill(0);\n\n            // Define the input and output data\n            let inputs = Array(100).fill(0).map(() => Math.random());\n            let outputs = Array(100).fill(0);\n\n            // Train the network\n            for (let epoch = 0; epoch < 1000; epoch++) {\n                backpropagation(w, b, inputs, outputs, w, 3, 1000);\n            }\n\n            // Print the final output\n            console.log(\"Final output:\", dotProduct(w, inputs));\n        }\n\n        // Call the main function\n        main();\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
